<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ubmitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Eurogroup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> for Animals</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission Date: 14 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Organisation overview</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Eurogroup for Animals is an international, non-governmental organisation that acts as the leading voice for </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">animal welfare at the European Union level providing a voice for the billions of animals kept in laboratories, farms and homes or living in the wild. As a federation of 40 animal welfare organisations across Europe</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, we mobilise millions of citizens to def</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">end the welfare of animals and act to ensure European, national and local decision makers take note and respond to our concerns.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Reason</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> for written submission</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As an animal welfare policy organisation, we believe strongly that scientific evidence exists </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">justifying the prohibition of primates as pets. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Several of our member organisations operate rescue centres and sanctuaries for confiscated and unwanted exotic pets</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and are well</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acquainted with welfare suffering of primates being unsuitably kept as pets. A few of these organisations (e.g. RSPCA, One Kind, Stichting AAP) will be submitting</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> detailed</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence directly on this issue</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regarding the number of animals rescued and related </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welfare concerns. Therefore, we are focusing our submission of evidence to studies and statements by experts documenting the risks of primate pet keeping and related trade. Furthermore, we provide evidence of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the regulatory actions by other European countr</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies to restrict the keeping of primates as pets.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primates are unsuitable for keeping as pets on the grounds of animal welfare, health and safety, and species conservation. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At least 15 European countries restrict</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or outright prohibit</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he keeping of primates as pets</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the UK should follow suit.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stud</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highlight welfare impacts of primate pet keeping and distorted perceptions from use in entertainment. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scientists and veterinarians caution against keeping primates as pets. </span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Comments</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primates are highly intelligent animals with specialised dietary, social and environmental needs that are difficult, if not impossible, to meet in a household environment. Primates of all ages and size can pose a significant physical and health threat to o</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wners. Many primates, including great apes, are still sourced from the wild, threatening wild populations </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and contributing to biodiversity loss</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Health &amp; safety risks to humans</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primates pose a significant health risks to humans due to their phylogenetic</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proximity. Furthermore, they can inflict severe bites and injuries to humans. A bibliogra</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">phic review of zoonotic disease</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> risks from exotic pets commissioned by Eurogroup for Animals identified a number of zoonoses (diseases spread between animals and huma</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns) documented in primates, including: rabies, monkey B virus, tuberculosis, Ebola virus, as well as zoonoses transmitted through bites and parasites</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Endangered species </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The trade in primates for pets has been linked to wild population declines in many</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> species. One of the most endangered primates, the Barbary macaque (</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Macaca sylvanus</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) from North Africa</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is suffering drastic declines due to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">habitat loss and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the illegal pet trade to Europe</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Trade Sustainability </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment of the free trade </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreement currently being</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">negotiated between the EU and Morocco documents this illegal trade</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UNEP’s Great Ape </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Survival Partnership report, Stolen Apes, estimates that 3000 chimpanzees, gorillas, bonobos and orangutans are lost </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">either sold, killed duri</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng the hunt, or dying in captivity)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the wild in Africa and Asia each year</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Examining confiscation records, international trade databases, law enforcement reports, and arrival rates from sanctuaries and rehabilitation centers between 2005 and 2011, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the report estimates that for every chimpanzee confiscated or confirmed in illegal trade, 10 more animals died during the capture</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or trafficking. Markets for tourist entertainment, disreputable zoos and pets are generating the demand and illegal permits ar</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e often used to traffic wild animals. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Legislative restrictions on the keeping of primates</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, Eurogroup for Animals conducted a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> comprehensive legislative review on the keeping and sale of exotic animals in 31 European countries</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The analysis</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> found </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that 22 countries restrict keeping</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of exotic animals as pets</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> based on negative lists of prohibited species</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Belgium is the one country that regulates keeping via a positive list of acceptable mammal species (this list does not include primates). </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The competent authority in Belgium has noted that a positive list has been a cost-effective and useful enforcement approach to regulating pets, as the public </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reports illegal sales online and in pet shops</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">People holding species not on the positive list at</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the time of its adoption were allowed to maintain their animals provided they registered them with the competent authority</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#c0504d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#c0504d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Netherlands has announced it will switch to a positive list for mammals in 2014 (primates are not allowed to be kept)</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Seve</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ral countries have included primates (or certain groups of primates) on their negative lists</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of species which cannot be kept as pets</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including: Austria, Bulgaria, Denmark, Estonia, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">France, Hungary, Italy, Latvia, Lithuania, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Portugal, Romania, and Sweden. The report contains tables summarising restrictions on the keeping and sale of exotic animals across European countries, as well as one-page country summ</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aries on legislative restrictions and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future legislative plans. An Executive </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ummary brochure is also available</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[xi]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Scientific studies examine primate pet keeping and use in entertainment</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A University of Bristol study on the welfare and suitability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">primates kept as pets concluded “it is unlikely that the welfare of pet primates can be adequately addressed in normal households” and argued the practice should end (Soulsbury et al. 2009)</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[xii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It noted that the majority of primate-related complaints received by the RSPCA between 2000-2005 concerned neglect. This might suggest owners are unaware and perhaps incapable of meeting the complex needs of primates in a household setting. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A study </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by Sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hroepher et al. 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">examining the use of chimpanzees in entertainment (e.g. movies, commercials, print advertisement) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suggested a strong distortion in the public’s view of chimpanzees as endangered species and suitability as pets</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[xiii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It noted the use of med</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with chimpanzees interacting with humans as “pets” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in non-range countries may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">encourage animal traffickers and poachers in range countries to capture infants for this market. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Scientists and veterinarians caution against primate pet keeping</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2013,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Federation of Veterinarians of Europe issued a policy statement calling on competent authorities to establish lists of animals to regulate the keeping of companion animals. It noted positive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lists may be preferable and that lists should be based on sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ientific criteria including “risks for the animals itself, its owners and the society, the indigenous species and ecosystems.”</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[xiv]</a></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the United States, a consumer information program on exotic pet choices called PetWatch</span><a name="_ednref15"></a><a href="#_edn15">[xv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was developed by EcoHealth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Alliance, an international organization of scientists focused on the conservation of biodiversity by examining the relationships between, wildlife, ecosystems and human health. A team of scientists conducted searches on </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">general, popular, industry and acad</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emic databases to acquire information</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on four criteria (</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">source sustainability, invasion threat, animal welfare and health threat) </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to generate a list of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Best, Fair and Worst choices of exotic pets. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The primate species assessed (</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g. common marmoset, rhe</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sus macaques, squirrel monkeys) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were all classified as “worst choices” and not recommended for pet keeping. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Confiscated and unwanted pet primates</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Several of Eurogroup for Animals’ member organisations </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">facilitate the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rescue </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">confiscated and unwanted pet primates each year. As </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stated</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some of these groups will be submitting written evidence directly</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and we would refer you to their submissions</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for data on the trade and keeping in the UK</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and related conclusions on the effec</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tiveness of the current </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regulations and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">code of practice</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. An indication of the types of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mammals (including primates)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in need of rescue</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in other EU Member States</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be found in the data published online by Stichting AAP (one of our Dutch member </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organisatio</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">): </span><a href="http://www.aap.nl/english/rescued-until-now.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.aap.nl/english/rescued-until-now.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://eurogroupforanimals.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://eurogroupforanimals.org</span></a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:9pt">, (including several organisations active in the UK: Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, One Kind, Dogs Trust, International Fund for Animal Welfare, World Society for the Protection of Animals and Human</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Arial 